<subSubSection pageId="66" pageNumber="67" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="66.[189,342,412,438]" box="[189,342,412,438]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,342,412,438]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,342,412,438]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Distribution</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="66.[189,1399,463,528]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
Coastal species, only known from Sambava in Sambava District, Sava Region (
<collectingRegion box="[1132,1390,463,490]" country="Madagascar" name="Antsiranana" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Antsiranana Province</collectingRegion>
) (
<figureCitation box="[199,308,502,528]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="88.[189,232,1752,1778]" captionTargetBox="[390,1182,270,1707]" captionTargetId="figure-11@88.[363,1224,265,1712]" captionTargetPageId="88" captionText="Fig. 23. Distribution maps of Malagasy species of Paracephaelis. A. P. aristata De Block sp. nov. (black dot), P. bardotiae De Block sp. nov. (blue dot), P. capitulifera De Block sp. nov. (green dot), P. gautieri De Block sp. nov. (red dot), and P. grandifructa De Block sp. nov. (yellow dot). B. P. cinerea (A.Rich. ex DC.) De Block (black dot). C. P. longipedicellata De Block sp. nov. (black dot), P. orientalis De Block sp. nov. (blue dot), P. pauciflora De Block sp. nov. (green dot), P. ranirisonii De Block sp. nov. (red dot), and P. seyrigii De Block sp. nov. (yellow dot). D. P. russata De Block sp. nov. (black dot), P. sambavensis De Block sp. nov. (blue dot), P. saxatilis (Scott Elliot) De Block (green dot), P. sericea (Arènes) De Block (red dot), and P. tiliacea Baill. (yellow dot)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6358868" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6358868/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Fig. 23D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="66.[189,476,571,597]" box="[189,476,571,597]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,476,571,597]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,476,571,597]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Habitat and phenology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="66.[189,1049,621,648]" box="[189,1049,621,648]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Littoral forest; on sand. Flowers: November (flowers buds); Fruits: April.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="66.[189,557,690,717]" box="[189,557,690,717]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,557,690,717]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,557,690,717]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Provisional IUCN assessment</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="66.[187,1400,741,1627]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
Critically Endangered: CR B2ab(iii). 
<taxonomicName authority="Block, 2022" authorityName="De Block" authorityYear="2022" box="[611,927,741,767]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rubiaceae" genus="Paracephaelis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gentianales" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sambavensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[611,927,741,767]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Paracephaelis sambavensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[932,1019,742,768]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is only known from 
<specimenCount box="[1250,1393,741,767]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" type="generic">2 specimens</specimenCount>
, seemingly collected from the same tree with a time lapse of ca 5 months. As a result, the EOO cannot be calculated and the AOO is 
<quantity box="[555,616,819,845]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" unit="km" value="4.0">4 km</quantity>
<superScript attach="left" box="[616,625,819,833]" fontSize="6" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">2</superScript>
, which complies with the Critically Endangered category under criterion B2. The species is known from a single location, which also complies with the Critically Endangered category under subcriterion ‘a’ of criterion B2. Both collections date from the sixties and no recent specimens are known. 
<taxonomicName authority="Block, 2022" authorityName="De Block" authorityYear="2022" box="[574,899,936,962]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rubiaceae" genus="Paracephaelis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gentianales" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sambavensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[574,899,936,962]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Paracephaelis sambavensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[907,998,937,963]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is a large tree from littoral forests on sand in north-eastern 
<collectingCountry box="[479,623,975,1001]" name="Madagascar" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
. These eastern littoral forests on sand were identified as one of the most biodiverse habitats for plants (
<bibRefCitation author="Dumetz N." box="[617,783,1015,1041]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" pagination="273 - 315" refId="ref67481" refString="Dumetz N. 1999. High plant diversity of lowland rainforest vestiges in eastern Madagascar. Biodiversity and Conservation 8: 273 - 315. https: // doi. org / 10.1023 / a: 1008880718889" type="journal article" year="1999">Dumetz 1999</bibRefCitation>
). They are home to ca 13% of Madagascar’s native plant species, even though they only occupy less than 1% of Madagascar’s surface (
<bibRefCitation author="Consiglio T. &amp; Schatz G. E. &amp; McPherson G. &amp; Lowry II P. P. &amp; Rabenantoandro J. &amp; Rogers Z. S. &amp; Rabevohitra R. &amp; Rabehevitra D." pageId="66" pageNumber="67" pagination="1799 - 1803" refId="ref66337" refString="Consiglio T., Schatz G. E., McPherson G., Lowry II P. P., Rabenantoandro J., Rogers Z. S., Rabevohitra R. &amp; Rabehevitra D. 2006. Deforestation and plant diversity of Madagascar's littoral forests. Conservation Biology 20: 1799 - 1803. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1523 - 1739.2006.00562. x" type="book chapter" year="2006">
Consiglio 
<emphasis box="[1337,1399,1053,1079]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">et al.</emphasis>
2006
</bibRefCitation>
). While littoral forests formed a continuous band along the east coast of 
<collectingCountry box="[1118,1260,1092,1118]" name="Madagascar" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
in the past, less than 10% now remain as isolated and fragmented patches (
<bibRefCitation author="Consiglio T. &amp; Schatz G. E. &amp; McPherson G. &amp; Lowry II P. P. &amp; Rabenantoandro J. &amp; Rogers Z. S. &amp; Rabevohitra R. &amp; Rabehevitra D." box="[953,1212,1132,1159]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" pagination="1799 - 1803" refId="ref66337" refString="Consiglio T., Schatz G. E., McPherson G., Lowry II P. P., Rabenantoandro J., Rogers Z. S., Rabevohitra R. &amp; Rabehevitra D. 2006. Deforestation and plant diversity of Madagascar's littoral forests. Conservation Biology 20: 1799 - 1803. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1523 - 1739.2006.00562. x" type="book chapter" year="2006">
Consiglio 
<emphasis box="[1078,1139,1132,1158]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">et al.</emphasis>
2006
</bibRefCitation>
). All remaining littoral forests are under severe pressure from local communities through logging for construction and firewood (
<bibRefCitation author="Consiglio T. &amp; Schatz G. E. &amp; McPherson G. &amp; Lowry II P. P. &amp; Rabenantoandro J. &amp; Rogers Z. S. &amp; Rabevohitra R. &amp; Rabehevitra D." box="[309,556,1210,1237]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" pagination="1799 - 1803" refId="ref66337" refString="Consiglio T., Schatz G. E., McPherson G., Lowry II P. P., Rabenantoandro J., Rogers Z. S., Rabevohitra R. &amp; Rabehevitra D. 2006. Deforestation and plant diversity of Madagascar's littoral forests. Conservation Biology 20: 1799 - 1803. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1523 - 1739.2006.00562. x" type="book chapter" year="2006">
Consiglio 
<emphasis box="[430,487,1210,1236]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">et al.</emphasis>
2006
</bibRefCitation>
), and this would certainly be the case around a large city as Sambava. As a large tree (
<quantity box="[332,393,1249,1276]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" unit="m" value="15.0">15 m</quantity>
tall), 
<taxonomicName authority="Block, 2022" authorityName="De Block" authorityYear="2022" box="[460,636,1249,1275]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rubiaceae" genus="Paracephaelis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gentianales" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sambavensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[460,636,1249,1275]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">P. sambavensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[643,733,1249,1275]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
would certainly be a sought-after resource. Furthermore, littoral forests in the region of Sambava have been cleared for slash-and-burn agriculture as well as for large-scale oil palm plantations (Google Earth, 
<date box="[741,938,1327,1353]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" value="2020-09">September 2020</date>
). Only a few remnant patches of littoral forest remain. Based on the above-mentioned facts, a reduction in the extent and quality of the habitat of 
<taxonomicName authority="Block, 2022" authorityName="De Block" authorityYear="2022" box="[221,398,1405,1431]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rubiaceae" genus="Paracephaelis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gentianales" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sambavensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[221,398,1405,1431]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">P. sambavensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[406,497,1406,1432]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is inferred. This threat, combined with the low AOO and the single location, qualifies 
<taxonomicName authority="Block, 2022" authorityName="De Block" authorityYear="2022" box="[295,472,1444,1470]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rubiaceae" genus="Paracephaelis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Gentianales" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sambavensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[295,472,1444,1470]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">P. sambavensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[479,569,1445,1471]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
for Critically Endangered status. The fact that the species has not been collected or observed for more than fifty years, would suggest it is possibly extinct. A targeted survey in the littoral forests of northern and north-eastern 
<collectingCountry box="[753,895,1522,1548]" name="Madagascar" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
is needed to confirm or deny the suspicion that the species is extinct in the wild. If living plants of this species were to be found, they should be protected and an ex situ conservation program set up.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="66.[189,248,1670,1696]" box="[189,248,1670,1696]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,248,1670,1696]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,248,1670,1696]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Note</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="66.[188,1398,1720,1825]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
Since the collection labels give identical data for both 
<emphasis box="[822,1049,1720,1746]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Capuron 27702-SF</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[1104,1220,1720,1746]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">27121-SF</emphasis>
, it would seem that the 
<specimenCount box="[282,455,1759,1786]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" type="generic">two specimens</specimenCount>
were collected from a single tree, the collector returning to the locality to collect flowers after having found a specimen in fruit. This species was never collected again.
</paragraph>
